commentTextItems.html: McMillan drops it short, Perera swings around, glorious pull shot, four runs to the long leg fence, it is all over! Sri Lanka win

commentPostTextItems.html: Sri Lanka have pulled off a great win against the Kiwiws here at Colombo
Chasing 237 for a win, the Lankans were in all kind of problems, losing four top orser batsmen with just 27 runs on the board in 9 overs.
Marvan Atapattu (66) and Russel Arnold put together a brilliant partnership of 110 runs in 24.5 overs.
Atapattu was run out, going for a risky second, his desperate dive wasn't good enough to save him.
In the meanwhile Arnold kept the momentum going picking up singles and twos.
After the fall of Atapattu, Suresh perera walked in to the middle.
Though he called in the services of a runner, nothing could stop Perera from smashing the Kiwi bowling.
The victory came about in the 49th over, when Perera swung McMillan through long leg for a boundary.
McMillan finished with 3.3-0-35-0, easily the most expensive bowler and one wondered why he had to keep bowling himself.
The conditions were getting dark and the services of Daryl Tuffey (6-1-19-1) seemed to have been forgotten.
Arnold and Perera put together an unbeaten partnership of 103 runs in just 14.4 overs.
Sri Lanka were given an opportunity to win, they took it handsomely. Kiwis had their chances, somehow they managed to give it away to the Lankans.
Russel Arnold played a mighty role in this fantastic Sri Lankan win. He made an unbeaten 91 off 116 balls.
Arnold is the man of the Match too. Earlier in the day, Arnold picked up a wicket with the first ball of his the two spells he had.
Suresh Perera remained unbeaten on 56 made in 51 balls.
Sri Lanka now has 6 points after their third win. They are at the top of the table.
Tomorrow, India and New Zealand will battle it out, here, at the same venue
We will be back with you at 1000 Hrs Local time, 0930 IST, 0400 GMT tomorrow, with all the live action as it happens.
Kindly send in your comments/opinions to comms@cricinfo.com
Thank You and Good Evening from Colombo.

stories.title: Sri Lankan middle order bursts back to life
stories.summary:
Sri Lanka's under performing middle order burst back to life at the
Premadasa International Stadium today, as the home side completed a
five-wicket victory against New Zealand in the fourth match of the
Coca Cola Cup
